
MEMENTO
Personal Radio

Product Experience Specification
v1.0  —  April 2026

Less noise. More signal.

1. Product Vision
Memento Personal Radio is a personal, continuous, adaptive listening environment. It combines the ambient, zero-decision quality of traditional radio with content that is generated for and shaped around a single listener.
The core experience: you open the app, you see a dial, you turn it to a station, and it plays. No browsing. No choosing from a catalogue. No infinite scroll. A voice is already talking about something you care about, or music is already playing something that fits your mood. You drift in and out. You listen while you cook, commute, or fall asleep.
Over time, the stations learn. They adapt to your interests, your rhythms, your depth. They remember where you left off. They never repeat. And they wait for you when you are away.


2. Core Principles
2.1 Audio-First, Screen-Second
Audio is the only medium that does not compete with the body. Eyes and hands remain free. The screen exists only as a minimal control surface: the dial, the bookmark button, the occasional steering input. If you never look at the screen after tapping play, the product has succeeded.
2.2 Subtractive, Not Additive
Memento replaces the morning doomscroll, the aimless podcast browse, the guilty screen time. It does not add another app to check. If it creates a new obligation, it has failed.
2.3 Push by Default, Pull by Choice
Content arrives. The morning brief is ready at 7am. The stations are pre-loaded. The user does not need to seek, configure, or decide. But when they want to steer, they can — conversationally, not through settings pages.
2.4 Agency Without Friction
The user always has control — they can skip, steer, create, retire. But they never have to exercise that control. The system works well on autopilot. Control is available, not required.


3. Information Architecture
3.1 The Daily Brief
The daily brief is not a station. It is a discrete delivery — a finite audio segment that arrives each morning, covers what matters to the user today, and ends. It sits above the stations as a card or notification: “Your brief is ready.” The user taps, listens for 10–15 minutes, and it is done.
The brief is personalized to the user’s chosen topics (industry news, specific interests, local context). It does not loop or generate continuous content. It is today’s brief and only today’s.
Design Note
The daily brief exists outside the station paradigm because it has a natural end. Stations are continuous; the brief is finite. Conflating the two creates the problem of a “brief station” that has nothing to say at 3pm.


