3.3 Two Station Categories
Structured stations (Curiosity 1 & 2) have memory and wait for the user. Content is segmented. The station resumes from where the user left off, with a brief contextual re-entry. These stations respect the user’s entry point — each segment begins cleanly, without requiring knowledge of prior segments.

Flow stations (Ambient Music, Contemplative Stream) are stateless and always fresh. There is no narrative thread to resume. The user enters a mood, not a story. These stations feel “already in progress” — the user tunes into something ongoing.


4. User Journey
4.1 First Open
The user opens the app for the first time. They see a warm, inviting text field: “What are you curious about?”
Below the text field, a set of 8–10 tappable topic tiles serves as a fallback: History, Science, Music, Technology, Philosophy, How the World Works, etc. These are visually quieter than the text input — a helping hand, not the primary path.
Design Hierarchy
Free text input is the primary path (captures genuine curiosity in the user’s own words). Tappable topics are the fallback (for users who prefer to browse rather than type). Both paths produce the same result: the system generates the initial stations and begins playing audio immediately.


From the single input, the system generates the user’s first stations. Audio begins playing within seconds. There is no confirmation screen, no “here are your stations, would you like to customize?” The user gave a seed; the system is already talking.
4.2 Daily Use — The Core Loop
The home screen is the dial. The stations are the entire interface. Each station has a visual identity — a colour, a texture, a name — that communicates mood without words. The user turns the dial to a station. It plays.

Key properties of the core loop:
Instant start. Content is pre-generated. No loading, no “generating your content.” Audio is ready on tap.
Static between stations. As the user turns the dial, they hear brief sonic hints of each station — a half-second of ambient music, a murmur of a voice — with static between. Landing on a station, the audio settles and clarifies.
Instant switching. No confirmation dialogs. Tap another station, it starts. The station you left continues internally — when you return, structured stations resume; flow stations are fresh.
Minimal screen. While listening: the station’s visual identity, a single line of text showing the current topic or track, and the bookmark button. Nothing else.
4.3 The Retro Dial
The dial interface uses a retro radio aesthetic. This is a deliberate emotional choice. A physical radio dial carries associations of warmth, analog imperfection, something your parents had in the kitchen. It communicates: “This is not another tech product.” The interaction should feel tactile — a turn, a landing, a settling-in.
4.4 Return After Absence
The user has not opened the app in several days. Nothing happened while they were gone. The stream exists for them alone; there is no broadcast running in their absence.

Structured stations resume. The curiosity station picks up where the user left off, with a brief contextual re-entry: “So, we were talking about how Mughal trade networks connected the subcontinent to Central Asia...” Then it continues.
Flow stations are fresh. Ambient music and the contemplative stream are always new. No gap to acknowledge.
The daily brief is today’s. Not three stacked briefs from missed days. Just today. Fresh start.
Key Insight
This is not a broadcast. Nothing plays when the user is not listening. Structured stations wait. This patience is part of what makes the product feel personal — no podcast drops whether you finished the last one or not. Memento has nowhere else to be.



5. Steering — How the User Shapes Their Experience
Steering is the mechanism by which users exert control over their stations. The design challenge: make control available without making it visible at all times. The principle is that steering should feel like talking to a DJ, not configuring software.
5.1 Intent Classification
User intents cluster into four categories, each requiring a different interaction pattern.

Category A: In-the-Moment Reactions
Interaction pattern: Gesture controls — buttons, swipes, taps. Zero thought required.
Skip — Move to the next segment or track. No opinion on what comes next.
Bookmark — Save this moment. One tap. The stream continues.
Pause / Resume — Hold my place on a structured station.
More like this — Signal approval. The stream leans into the current direction.
Category B: Adjusting Station Direction
Interaction pattern: Contextual dropdown options + free text input.
When the user wants to shift what a station covers without leaving it, a dropdown reveals preset options relevant to the station type. Below the presets, a free text field allows precise steering.

