Category C: Structural Changes
Interaction pattern: Deliberate actions — separate CTAs, infrequent, can afford more friction.
Create a new station — Same flow as onboarding: text input with topic fallbacks.
Retire a station — Long-press or dedicated action. Frees the slot.
Rename / reframe — The station started as “Indian history” but evolved; acknowledge the drift.
Category D: Daily Brief Controls
Interaction pattern: Simple list management.
Add or remove topics from the brief.
Change delivery time.
Adjust length (shorter / longer).
5.2 Implicit Steering
Beyond explicit actions, the system learns from behaviour. Segments skipped, segments completed, time of day each station is used, how long the user stays, which bookmarks are made. These signals continuously refine the stations without requiring any user input.


6. Bookmarks
A bookmark is a discrete piece of content pulled out of the stream. On a structured station, it is a specific segment (the one about Mughal trade networks). On the ambient music station, it is a track. On the contemplative stream, it is a particular quote or fragment.
One tap while listening. The stream continues. The bookmark is saved.
6.1 The Bookmark Library
Bookmarks live in a simple, chronological library. Not organized by station — organized by time. A timeline of moments that caught the user’s attention.
“Mughal Trade Networks — Indian History station — April 3”
“Marcus Aurelius on impermanence — Contemplative — April 5”
“Saved ambient track — Music — April 7”
The user taps any bookmark to replay it. Over time, the bookmark library becomes an unintentional self-portrait — a collection the user did not deliberately curate, but which reflects what resonated.
6.2 Bookmarks as Signal
Bookmarked content feeds back into the system’s understanding of what the user cares about. A bookmarked segment on Mughal economics is a stronger signal than simply listening to it. This informs future content generation without requiring explicit feedback.


7. History & Progress
Users need a sense of accumulation — “What have I gained from my time here?” This is answered through two layers, inspired by Letterboxd’s diary model and Strava’s heatmap.
7.1 The Listening Diary
The default view. A chronological, day-by-day record of what the user listened to. Simple, low-effort, always growing.
Monday — 25 min Indian History (Mughal economics), 40 min ambient music, morning brief.
Tuesday — 15 min brief, 1 hr ambient music, 20 min contemplative stream.
This is a journal the user did not have to write. It is always available, but never pushed. The user glances at it when they want to — daily, weekly, or rarely.
7.2 The Exploration Visualization
An optional, higher-level view available when the user wants to zoom out. This is not a pre-drawn map with empty nodes to fill — it is a picture that emerges purely from what the user has already covered.
Only shows explored territory. New nodes appear as the user encounters topics, not before. No implied completeness. No finish line.
Density communicates depth. Areas where the user spent more time appear denser. Edges are sparser. The shape reflects attention, not a curriculum.
Grows at the pace of listening. After a week, perhaps twelve nodes. After a month, forty. Always proportional to the user’s investment.
Doubles as navigation. Tapping a node lets the user say “go back to this” or “go deeper here.” History becomes a steering mechanism.
Why Not Progress Bars or Metrics?
Episode counts imply a syllabus with a completion state. Minutes-listened feels like a fitness tracker. Streaks create guilt. The visualization avoids all of these by showing the shape of curiosity rather than measuring it. There is no number going up — only a territory filling in.



8. Evolution Over Time
8.1 Day-to-Day Adaptation
The system observes skips, completions, and bookmarks. Tomorrow’s content reflects today’s behaviour. A user who skips military history and bookmarks economics segments will receive more economics, less military. No explicit input required.
8.2 Week-to-Week Pattern Recognition
Broader patterns emerge: which stations are used at which times, how long sessions last, weekend versus weekday behaviour. The system optimizes content length to match observed habits (e.g., commute-length segments for the station used during commutes).
8.3 Month-to-Month Drift
Over weeks, interests naturally drift. The “Indian history” station may quietly become an “economic history” station based on what the user engaged with. The system may surface this as a natural acknowledgment within the content, and may suggest spinning off a new station based on the deeper curiosity it has detected.
8.4 The Surprise Counterweight
To prevent filter-bubble narrowing, approximately one in five segments is deliberately adjacent — not random, but unexpected. An Indian history station might introduce Ottoman economics or Chinese trade routes. The ambient music station occasionally surfaces unfamiliar genres sharing sonic qualities with what the user likes. The system earns trust through accuracy, then spends it on occasional surprise.


9. Design Language
Retro radio aesthetic. The dial, the static between stations, the warm visual identity. This signals “not another tech product” and creates an emotional frame of warmth and nostalgia.
Minimal screen while listening. Station visual identity, one line of current content, bookmark button. The screen is something you glance at, not stare at.
Consistent input pattern. Whenever the user needs to express intent: tappable options first, free text underneath. Same pattern at onboarding, while steering, when creating stations.
No metrics on the home screen. No streak counters, no minutes listened, no badges. The home screen is the dial. The diary and visualization live deeper, available but never pushed.


10. What This Is Not
Not a podcast app. Podcasts are discrete episodes you choose. Memento is a continuous stream you enter.
Not a music streaming service. Music is one station among five. The product is about the full spectrum of audio experience: information, music, contemplation, briefing.
Not a meditation app. The contemplative stream is not guided breathing or mindfulness exercises. It is ambient presence with fragments of meaning.
Not a news app. The daily brief covers the user’s interests, but the product is not organized around current events.
Not a learning management system. There are no courses, no quizzes, no certifications. The curiosity stations explore; they do not teach to a test.


11. Future Feature: Bookmark Import as Personalization
This is an additional specification for a future feature, not part of the core launch experience.

11.1 The Insight
A user’s saved bookmarks — from Pocket, Raindrop, browser bookmarks, YouTube watch-later lists, Instapaper — are the most honest record of their curiosity. Not what they told people they’re interested in, but what they quietly saved for later. Most of which they never went back to.
The gap between bookmarking and consuming is exactly the space Memento is designed to fill. Bookmark import lets the system understand the full landscape of a user’s curiosity from day one, rather than building it slowly from a single text input.
11.2 How It Works
The user connects a bookmarking service or imports a browser export. The system scans the saved items — not to replay that content as audio, but to extract the shape of the user’s interests. Fourteen saved articles about urban design, eight about Indian history, a cluster of videos about jazz theory. From these signals, the system generates stations that already feel informed.
This is a personalization input, not a content pipeline. The bookmarks tell the system what topics to cover, at what depth, and with what emphasis. The actual audio content is still generated fresh by the system.
11.3 Placement in the User Journey
Bookmark import should not be part of first-open onboarding. The primary path remains: type your curiosity, get stations, start listening. Import is a second-session or settings-level action.
Possible triggers:
A quiet nudge after the first full day of use: “Want your stations to know you better? Import your bookmarks.”
An option in the station settings: “Refine this station with your saved reading.”
A permanent option in profile/settings, available but never pushed.
11.4 Supported Sources
Pocket, Raindrop, Instapaper (via API integration)
Browser bookmark export (HTML file)
YouTube watch-later / liked videos
Kindle highlights and notes (if accessible)
Read-later lists from RSS readers (Feedly, etc.)
11.5 The Emotional Pitch
Bookmark import addresses a specific guilt that many users carry: the growing list of things they saved but never returned to. Memento can reframe this positively: “You saved all this because it mattered to you. We’ll turn it into something you can actually listen to while you live your life.”
The bookmarks are not wasted. They become the seed data for a listening experience shaped around the user’s genuine — if sometimes forgotten — curiosities.


12. Open Questions for Future Exploration
How many stations should the maximum be? Is five the right ceiling, or should users be able to add more over time?
Should the contemplative stream allow user-contributed content (their own quotes, their own reflections) alongside AI-curated material?
What is the right model for the daily brief — purely AI-generated, or aggregating from real sources with AI synthesis?
How should the product handle multiple users in a household (e.g., shared listening on a speaker)?
What is the monetization model? Subscription feels most aligned with the product’s values (no ads, no attention extraction).
How does voice selection work? Should users choose a voice for each station, or should the system assign voices based on station personality?
Social features: should users ever be able to share a station configuration, a bookmark collection, or a listening diary?

This document captures the product experience as designed through collaborative exploration. Technical implementation, architecture, and infrastructure requirements are deferred to a separate specification.
